references: We compare our results with previous state-of-the-art human pose estimation models, including SimpleBaseline, Cascaded Pyramid Network (CPN), Hourglass, and HRNet, and show the results in Table. 1. As it shows, our two models with concatenation and element-wise sum, respectively, both achieve a better result on AP50superscript50AP^{50}, AP75superscript75AP^{75} and APMsuperscriptAP^{M}, and have 3.5% improvement on ARAR. Besides that, Swin-L with element-wise sum achieves the same APAP as HRNet-W48.

references: An ablation study is chosen to determine the factor of input resolution that affects the performance. The results of our model based on Swin-L are presented in Table. 2, with two fusion methods, and input resolution set to 224224224224224\times 224 and 384384384384384\times 384, respectively. As shown in the table, comparing experiments 5, 6, 7 and 8, with the input resolution increased, the average precision has increased by 3.4 points for both fusion methods, with the price of a significant larger GFLOPs.

The experiments were conducted over the different sizes of Swin-B and Swin-L. As shown in the Table. 2, comparing the two results between experiments 3 and 5, it can be seen that the larger size of backbone only contributes limited improvements to its results. Similarly, no significant increase was found in experiment 4 compared with experiment 7. In addition, the computation cost and model size increase significantly, as the result of the growing FLOPs and number of parameters.
Overall, these results indicate the trade-offs between precision and computation cost. A smaller backbone should be selected if the computation cost is of higher priority.
In summary, it can be seen from the data in Table. 2, these results show that the computation cost of concatenation is slightly higher than the element-wise sum.
